class TwoLayerNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_dim, hidden_dim, output_dim):
        super().__init__()
        self.fc1  = nn.Linear(input_dim, hidden_dim)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        self.fc2  = nn.Linear(hidden_dim, output_dim)
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.relu(self.fc1(x))
        return self.fc2(x)

# DataLoaders
train_ds    = TensorDataset(X_train, y_train)
train_loader= DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size=32, shuffle=True)
val_ds      = TensorDataset(X_test,  y_test)
val_loader  = DataLoader(val_ds,   batch_size=32, shuffle=False)

# Model, optimizer, loss
model = TwoLayerNN(input_dim=12, hidden_dim=256, output_dim=2)
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3)
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

for epoch in range(1, 201):
    # --- Training ---
    model.train()
    running_loss = 0.0
    correct_train = 0
    total_train   = 0

    for xb, yb in train_loader:
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        logits = model(xb)
        loss   = criterion(logits, yb)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()

        running_loss += loss.item() * xb.size(0)
        preds = logits.argmax(dim=1)
        correct_train += (preds == yb).sum().item()
        total_train   += xb.size(0)

    train_loss = running_loss / total_train
    train_acc  = correct_train / total_train

    # --- Validation ---
    model.eval()
    correct_val = 0
    total_val   = 0
    with torch.no_grad():
        for xb, yb in val_loader:
            logits = model(xb)
            preds  = logits.argmax(dim=1)
            correct_val += (preds == yb).sum().item()
            total_val   += xb.size(0)
    val_acc = correct_val / total_val

    # --- Logging ---
    if epoch % 20 == 0 or epoch == 1:
        print(
            f"Epoch {epoch:3d} | "
            f"Train Loss: {train_loss:.4f} | "
            f"Train Acc: {train_acc:.3%} | "
            f"Val Acc:   {val_acc:.3%}"
        )

import numpy as np
import torch
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso
from captum.attr import Lime

class WrappedLasso:
    def __init__(self, alpha=1.0, fit_intercept=True, max_iter=10000):
        self.reg = Lasso(alpha=alpha, fit_intercept=fit_intercept, max_iter=max_iter)

    def fit(self, dataloader):
        # collect all perturbed inputs, outputs, and weights
        Xs, ys, ws = [], [], []
        for Xb, yb, wb in dataloader:
            Xs.append(Xb.numpy())
            ys.append(yb.numpy())
            ws.append(wb.numpy())
        X = np.vstack(Xs)
        y = np.concatenate(ys)
        sample_weight = np.concatenate(ws)
        # fit the sklearn Lasso with sample weights
        self.reg.fit(X, y, sample_weight=sample_weight)

    def representation(self):
        # return a torch tensor of coefficients (shape [d])
        return torch.tensor(self.reg.coef_, dtype=torch.float32)

# 1) make it sparser by upping alpha
wrapped_lasso = WrappedLasso(alpha=.5)

# 2) re‑init LIME with our wrapper
lime_explainer = Lime(
    forward_func=model,
    interpretable_model=wrapped_lasso
)

# 3) explain as before
input_ex   = X_test[10].unsqueeze(0)
true_label = y_test[10].item()
attr = lime_explainer.attribute(
    input_ex,
    target=true_label,
    n_samples=500
)

print("Sparse LIME attributions:", attr.detach().numpy().flatten())

import torch
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# --- 1) Pick up the example and compute per‑feature σ from the train set
example    = X_test[10].unsqueeze(0)    # [1, d]
true_label = y_test[10].item()
n_samples  = 500

# Use the training data distribution for noise scale
# Here we focus on the first two informative features (idx 0,1)
sigma0 = X_train[:, 0].std().item()
sigma1 = X_train[:, 1].std().item()

# --- 2) Generate perturbed neighborhood
# Start by tiling the example
noise0 = torch.normal(mean=example[0,0], std=sigma0, size=(n_samples,))
noise1 = torch.normal(mean=example[0,1], std=sigma1, size=(n_samples,))
# Create a batch of perturbed inputs
perturbed = example.repeat(n_samples, 1)  # [n_samples, d]
perturbed[:, 0] = noise0
perturbed[:, 1] = noise1

# --- 3) Get model probabilities for class 1
model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    logits = model(perturbed)
    probs  = torch.softmax(logits, dim=1)[:, 1].cpu().numpy()

# --- 4) Plot
pert_np = perturbed.cpu().numpy()
orig_np  = example.cpu().numpy()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sc = plt.scatter(
    pert_np[:, 0], pert_np[:, 1],
    c=probs, cmap='viridis', alpha=0.7
)
plt.colorbar(sc, label='P(class=1)')

plt.scatter(
    orig_np[0, 0], orig_np[0, 1],
    color='red', marker='*', s=200,
    label=f"Original example (label={true_label})"
)

plt.xlabel("Feature 1")
plt.ylabel("Feature 2")
plt.title("Noisy Neighborhood & Model P(class=1)")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

from captum.attr import Saliency, NoiseTunnel, GuidedGradCam

# Load pretrained ResNet-152
model = models.resnet152(pretrained=True)
model.eval()

# 2) Preprocessing transform (ImageNet standard)
preprocess = T.Compose([
    T.Resize(256),
    T.CenterCrop(224),
    T.ToTensor(),
    T.Normalize(
        mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
        std= [0.229, 0.224, 0.225]
    )
])

# 3) Utility to load & preprocess an image
def load_image(path, device='cpu'):
    img = Image.open(path).convert('RGB')
    tensor = preprocess(img).unsqueeze(0).to(device)  # [1,3,224,224]
    return tensor, img

# 4) Paths & labels (you can change these)
image_info = [
    ('dog.jpg',      'Dog'),
    ('tabby.jpg',    'Tabby Cat'),
    ('airplane.jpg','Airplane')
]

# 5) Saliency methods
saliency      = Saliency(model)
smoothgrad    = NoiseTunnel(saliency)
guided_cam    = GuidedGradCam(model, model.layer4[-1])

# 6) Loop over images and compute maps
device = torch.device('cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu')
model.to(device)

import matplotlib.colors as mcolors
fig, axes = plt.subplots(len(image_info), 4, figsize=(16, 4*len(image_info)))
norm = mcolors.Normalize(vmin=0, vmax=1)

for i, (fname, title) in enumerate(image_info):
    # a) Load
    inp_tensor, orig_img = load_image(fname, device)
    inp_tensor.requires_grad_()
    
    # b) Forward & pick top‑1 class
    out = model(inp_tensor)
    _, pred = out.max(1)
    
    # c1) Vanilla Gradients
    grad_vanilla = saliency.attribute(inp_tensor, target=pred.item())
    
    # c2) SmoothGrad
    grad_smooth = smoothgrad.attribute(
        inp_tensor,
        nt_type='smoothgrad',
        stdevs=0.1,
        nt_samples=50,
        target=pred.item()
    )
    
    # c3) Guided Grad‑CAM
    grad_guided_cam = guided_cam.attribute(
        inp_tensor, 
        target=pred.item()
    )
    # Upsample to input size
    grad_guided_cam = nn.functional.interpolate(
        grad_guided_cam, size=(224,224), mode='bilinear', align_corners=False
    )
    
    # d) Convert to numpy heatmaps (take absolute and channel‑mean)
    def to_heatmap(attr):
        hm = attr.abs().sum(dim=1).squeeze().cpu().detach().numpy()
        hm = (hm - hm.min()) / (hm.max() - hm.min())
        return hm
    
    hm_vanilla = to_heatmap(grad_vanilla)
    hm_smooth  = to_heatmap(grad_smooth)
    hm_gcam    = to_heatmap(grad_guided_cam)
    
    # 1) Original image
    axes[i,0].imshow(orig_img)
    axes[i,0].set_title(f"{title}\nPred: {pred.item()}")
    axes[i,0].axis('off')

    # 2) Vanilla Grad
    ax = axes[i,1]
    ax.imshow(orig_img)
    hm_im = ax.imshow(
        hm_vanilla,
        cmap='inferno',    # or cmap='hot'
        norm=norm,
        alpha=0.6
    )
    ax.set_title("Vanilla Grad")
    ax.axis('off')
    fig.colorbar(hm_im, ax=ax, fraction=0.046, pad=0.04, label="Saliency")

    # 3) SmoothGrad
    ax = axes[i,2]
    ax.imshow(orig_img)
    hm_im = ax.imshow(
        hm_smooth,
        cmap='inferno',    # or cmap='hot'
        norm=norm,
        alpha=0.6
    )
    ax.set_title("SmoothGrad")
    ax.axis('off')
    fig.colorbar(hm_im, ax=ax, fraction=0.046, pad=0.04, label="Saliency")

    # 4) Guided Grad‑CAM
    ax = axes[i,3]
    ax.imshow(orig_img)
    hm_im = ax.imshow(
        hm_gcam,
        cmap='inferno',    # or cmap='hot'
        norm=norm,
        alpha=0.6
    )
    ax.set_title("Guided Grad‑CAM")
    ax.axis('off')
    fig.colorbar(hm_im, ax=ax, fraction=0.046, pad=0.04, label="Saliency")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Attention Visualization and LIME for text¶

In [55]:
from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification
import torch
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# 1) Load tokenizer & fine‑tuned IMDB BERT (with attentions)
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained("textattack/bert-base-uncased-imdb")
model     = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(
    "textattack/bert-base-uncased-imdb",
    output_attentions=True
)
model.eval()

# 2) Two example reviews
texts = [
    "I absolutely loved this movie, it was fantastic!",
    "I hated this film, it was the worst."
]

for text in texts:
    # --- Tokenize & forward pass
    inputs  = tokenizer(text, return_tensors="pt")
    outputs = model(**inputs)
    attns   = outputs.attentions    # tuple of 12 layers: [1, heads, seq, seq]
    tokens  = tokenizer.convert_ids_to_tokens(inputs["input_ids"][0])
    seq_len = len(tokens)

    # --- Extract maps
    a0h0  = attns[0][0,0].detach().numpy()      # layer 0, head 0
    a11h0 = attns[11][0,0].detach().numpy()     # layer 11, head 0
    avg0  = attns[0][0].mean(0).detach().numpy()   # avg over heads
    avg5  = attns[5][0].mean(0).detach().numpy()
    avg11 = attns[11][0].mean(0).detach().numpy()

    # --- Roll‑out (multi‑hop)
    avg_attns = [att[0].mean(0).detach().numpy() for att in attns]
    aug  = [m + np.eye(seq_len) for m in avg_attns]
    norm = [m / m.sum(-1, keepdims=True) for m in aug]
    rollout = norm[0]
    for m in norm[1:]:
        rollout = rollout.dot(m)

    # --- Prepare lists
    maps   = [a0h0, a11h0, avg0, avg5, avg11, rollout]
    titles = ["L0 H0", "L11 H0", "Avg L0", "Avg L5", "Avg L11", "Roll‑Out"]

    # --- Filter out special tokens
    filter_idxs = [
        i for i, tok in enumerate(tokens)
        if tok not in ("[CLS]", "[SEP]", "[PAD]")
    ]
    filtered_tokens = [tokens[i] for i in filter_idxs]

    # --- Extract [CLS]→token rows and filter columns
    cls_idx = tokens.index("[CLS]")  # typically 0
    filtered_rows = [
        mat[cls_idx][filter_idxs]
        for mat in maps
    ]

    # --- Renormalize so each row sums to 1
    filtered_rows = [
        row / row.sum()
        for row in filtered_rows
    ]

    # --- Plot 2×3 bar charts of filtered & normalized attentions
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(18, 6), sharey=True)
    axes = axes.flatten()
    for ax, row, title in zip(axes, filtered_rows, titles):
        ax.bar(range(len(row)), row, color="C0")
        ax.set_title(title)
        ax.set_xticks(range(len(row)))
        ax.set_xticklabels(filtered_tokens, rotation=90, fontsize=8)
        ax.set_ylim(0, 1)
        ax.grid(axis="y", alpha=0.3)

    plt.suptitle(f"Normalized [CLS]→tokens Attention for: “{text}”", y=1.02)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# 1) Imports
import torch
import torch.nn.functional as F
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso
from transformers import AutoTokenizer, AutoModelForSequenceClassification
from captum.attr import LimeBase
from IPython.display import HTML, display

# 2) Load model/tokenizer
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained("textattack/bert-base-uncased-imdb")
model     = AutoModelForSequenceClassification.from_pretrained(
    "textattack/bert-base-uncased-imdb",
    output_attentions=False
)
model.eval()

# 3) Helper functions
def forward_func(text_tensor, *args):
    mask = (text_tensor != tokenizer.pad_token_id).long()
    return model(input_ids=text_tensor, attention_mask=mask).logits

def similarity_func(orig, pert, _):
    emb = model.get_input_embeddings()
    with torch.no_grad():
        o = emb(orig.squeeze(0)).mean(dim=0, keepdim=True)
        p = emb(pert.squeeze(0)).mean(dim=0, keepdim=True)
        dist = 1 - F.cosine_similarity(o, p)
    return torch.exp(-0.5 * dist**2)

def perturb_func(text_tensor, **kwargs):
    """
    Sample a random binary mask, but ensure at least one token survives
    so we never feed an empty sequence into BERT.
    """
    # text_tensor: [1, seq_len]
    prob = torch.full(text_tensor.shape, 0.5,
                      dtype=torch.float, device=text_tensor.device)
    mask = torch.bernoulli(prob).long()  # 0/1 mask

    # If all zeros, force the first token to survive
    if mask.sum().item() == 0:
        mask[0, 0] = 1
    return mask

def interp_to_input(interp_sample, original_input, **kwargs):
    # original_input: [1, seq_len], interp_sample mask: [1, seq_len]
    mask = interp_sample.bool().squeeze(0)      # [seq_len]
    # select tokens along the second dim
    return original_input[:, mask]              # shape [1, kept_len]

from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso

class WrappedLasso:
    def __init__(self, alpha=0.1, fit_intercept=True, max_iter=10000):
        self.reg = Lasso(alpha=alpha, fit_intercept=fit_intercept, max_iter=max_iter)

    def fit(self, dataloader):
        # collect all perturbed inputs, outputs, and sim-weights
        Xs, ys, ws = [], [], []
        for Xb, yb, wb in dataloader:
            Xs.append(Xb.numpy())
            ys.append(yb.numpy())
            ws.append(wb.numpy())
        X = np.vstack(Xs)
        y = np.concatenate(ys)
        w = np.concatenate(ws)
        # fit sklearn Lasso with sample_weight
        self.reg.fit(X, y, sample_weight=w)

    def representation(self):
        # return torch tensor of learned coefficients
        return torch.tensor(self.reg.coef_, dtype=torch.float32)

# 4) Build LimeBase
lime_base = LimeBase(
    forward_func=forward_func,
    interpretable_model=WrappedLasso(alpha=0.1),
    similarity_func=similarity_func,
    perturb_func=perturb_func,
    perturb_interpretable_space=True,
    to_interp_rep_transform=lambda inp, **kw: torch.ones_like(inp),
    from_interp_rep_transform=interp_to_input
)

# 5) Visualization helper
def show_text_attr(tokens, attributions):
    # Build the highlighted spans
    spans = ""
    for tok, attr in zip(tokens, attributions):
        color = "0,200,0" if attr > 0 else "200,0,0"
        alpha = min(abs(attr), 1.0)
        spans += f'<mark style="background-color:rgba({color},{alpha}); padding:2px;">{tok}</mark> '
    # Wrap in a white-background div
    html = (
        f'<div style="background-color:white; padding:10px; '
        f'border:1px solid #ddd; border-radius:4px; display:inline-block;">'
        f'<p style="font-size:16px; margin:0;">{spans}</p></div>'
    )
    display(HTML(html))

label_map = {0: "negative", 1: "positive"}

# 6) Explanation wrapper
def explain_review(review, n_samples=2000):
    # Tokenize
    tokens = tokenizer.tokenize(review)
    ids    = tokenizer.convert_tokens_to_ids(tokens)
    text_tensor = torch.tensor(ids).unsqueeze(0)

    # Predict
    logits = model(input_ids=text_tensor,
                   attention_mask=(text_tensor!=tokenizer.pad_token_id).long()).logits
    probs  = torch.softmax(logits, dim=1)[0]
    pred   = torch.argmax(probs).item()
    print(f"Prediction: {label_map[pred]} ({probs[pred]:.1%})\n")

    # LIME attributions
    attributions = lime_base.attribute(
        inputs=text_tensor,
        target=torch.tensor([pred]),
        additional_forward_args=(),
        n_samples=n_samples,
        show_progress=False
    ).squeeze(0).detach().numpy()

    # Normalize
    attributions = attributions / np.linalg.norm(attributions, ord=1)
    show_text_attr(tokens, attributions)

# 7) Demo
explain_review("I absolutely loved this movie.", n_samples = 1000)
explain_review("This movie was a terrible waste of time. I hated every minute.", n_samples = 1000)
explain_review("Probably one of the worst adaptations in existence. The only series more disappointing is the last two seasons of Game of Thrones.", n_samples = 1000)
explain_review("Still the most violent, emotional, and existential crisis-inducing show on TV.", n_samples = 1000)
explain_review("How annoying, Bizarro was repeated too many times. The rest was funny though...Turtle Face...lol. I'm helping, I'm Helping", n_samples = 1000)
